01

Motivation & Problem Statement

Professional investment research requires synthesizing information across multiple domains simultaneously: macroeconomic trends, company fundamentals, market technicals, competitive positioning, and portfolio-level risk exposure. This typically involves toggling between Bloomberg terminals, screening tools, charting platforms, and spreadsheets ‚Äî a fragmented workflow that introduces latency, cognitive overhead, and missed cross-domain signals.

FRANK'S LOOK FOR ALPHA addresses this by building a unified platform that:

  • Automates the research pipeline ‚Äî A LangGraph-based multi-agent system decomposes research into specialized steps, each handled by a purpose-built AI agent
  • Fuses quantitative and qualitative analysis ‚Äî Combines programmatic indicator calculations with LLM-generated investment theses that contextualize numbers within the broader narrative
  • Delivers actionable output ‚Äî Every analysis culminates in a concrete signal, score, or recommendation backed by real data
  • Runs locally ‚Äî All data processing happens on your machine; only LLM inference calls leave the network

LangGraph Agent Orchestration

The macro research pipeline uses a directed acyclic graph (DAG) with human-in-the-loop:

üîç Researcher
‚Üí
üìä Sentiment
‚Üí
üíº Portfolio
‚Üí
‚è∏Ô∏è Human Review
‚Üí

Each node is a LangChain agent powered by Gemini 3 Pro. The graph uses MemorySaver for state persistence and supports interrupt_before=["writer"], allowing the user to review preliminary findings before committing to a final report.

Core Features

1 ¬∑ Multi-Agent Macro Research Pipeline

Enter any macro topic ‚Äî "Impact of AI on semiconductor industry", "Federal Reserve rate cut implications" ‚Äî and the system dispatches four specialized AI agents in sequence:

Agent Function Data Sources
Researcher Gathers macro data, market prices, news yfinance, DuckDuckGo
Sentiment Scores market mood (‚àí1 to +1), identifies drivers LLM-interpreted news
Portfolio Maps findings to your holdings, flags risk User's XLSX + yfinance
Writer Synthesizes a structured investment memo All upstream outputs

Real-time SSE streaming shows each agent's progress ‚Äî the user watches steps complete live in the stepper UI. Reports are automatically persisted to SQLite for later retrieval.

Dashboard showing completed research pipeline with progress stepper and generated report

2 ¬∑ Fundamental Deep Dive & AI Thesis

Enter a ticker to receive a quantamental scorecard paired with an AI-generated investment thesis. The scorecard surfaces institutional-grade metrics:

Metric Why It Matters
Forward P/E Valuation relative to expected earnings
PEG Ratio Growth-adjusted P/E for GARP screening
Profit Margin Pricing power and competitive moat indicator
ROE Capital efficiency ‚Äî Buffett's preferred metric
Debt/Equity Balance sheet health and financial risk
Revenue Growth Top-line momentum signal

The AI thesis contextualizes metrics against the current macro environment. If you researched "AI infrastructure spending", the NVDA thesis will connect 62.5% revenue growth to the macro tailwind.

Fundamental Deep Dive for NVDA ‚Äî $4.45T market cap, 53% profit margin, AI-generated "Strong Buy" thesis

3 ¬∑ Technical Analysis Engine

Full technical charting suite computed server-side and rendered with interactive Plotly candlestick charts:

  • SMA-50 / SMA-200 ‚Äî Trend identification and golden/death cross detection
  • RSI-14 ‚Äî Momentum oscillator with overbought (>70) / oversold (<30) zones
  • MACD (12, 26, 9) ‚Äî Trend momentum with signal line crossovers
  • Bollinger Bands (20, 2œÉ) ‚Äî Volatility envelope and mean-reversion signals
  • Support / Resistance ‚Äî Rolling 20-period local minima/maxima

Each signal is rendered as a color-coded badge (green/bullish, red/bearish, neutral) alongside the price chart.

Technical Analysis ‚Äî Candlestick with SMA overlays, RSI sub-chart, MACD histogram with bullish crossover signal

4 ¬∑ Competitor Comparison & Peer Benchmarking

Automatically discovers industry peers via hybrid retrieval (yfinance metadata + DuckDuckGo search + LLM extraction) and generates three-layer output:

Layer Visualization Insight
Comparison Table Side-by-side metrics Relative valuation gaps
Radar Chart Multi-dimensional positioning Visual strength/weakness mapping
AI Analysis LLM-generated narrative Actionable competitive intelligence
Competitor Comparison ‚Äî Fundamentals table, radar chart, and AI-generated comparative analysis

5 ¬∑ AI Stock Idea Screener

Describe an investment theme in natural language ‚Äî "AI infrastructure stocks under $50B", "high-dividend energy" ‚Äî and the system searches markets, extracts tickers via LLM, fetches fundamentals, and ranks with AI-generated conviction scores. Uses SSE for real-time two-phase progress.

Research streaming with real-time SSE progress updates and Stock Idea Screener

6 ¬∑ Sector Performance Heatmap

Interactive Plotly treemap showing all 11 GICS sectors via ETFs (XLE, XLF, XLK, XLV, etc.). Block size proportional to performance magnitude, color-coded green‚Üíred. Period toggles for 1D, 1W, 1M, YTD. Auto-loads on page load for immediate market context.

Sector Performance Heatmap ‚Äî 11 GICS sectors with YTD period toggle

7 ¬∑ Portfolio Risk Analytics

Upload your portfolio (XLSX/CSV) for institutional-grade analytics:

  • Sharpe & Sortino Ratios ‚Äî Risk-adjusted returns
  • Maximum Drawdown ‚Äî Worst peak-to-trough decline
  • Beta ‚Äî Portfolio sensitivity to S&P 500
  • VaR (95%) ‚Äî Value at Risk at 95% confidence
  • Tracking Error ‚Äî Active risk relative to benchmark

Visualizations include composition charts, benchmark overlays, risk-return scatter plots, drawdown series, and monthly return heatmaps. The Portfolio Agent cross-references holdings against researched topics.

8 ¬∑ Research History & Persistence

All completed reports are stored in SQLite with full-text content. Browse past reports with topic summaries and timestamps, reload historical reports, delete outdated analyses, and compare sentiment scores across topics over time.

05

Quantitative Methods

Technical Indicator Computation

All indicators are computed server-side using vectorized pandas operations:

# RSI (Relative Strength Index) ‚Äî Wilder's smoothing
delta = df['Close'].diff()
gain = delta.where(delta > 0, 0).rolling(14).mean()
loss = (-delta.where(delta < 0, 0)).rolling(14).mean()
rs = gain / loss
rsi = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))

# Bollinger Bands ‚Äî 20-period SMA ¬± 2œÉ
bb_mid = df['Close'].rolling(20).mean()
bb_std = df['Close'].rolling(20).std()
bb_upper = bb_mid + 2 * bb_std
bb_lower = bb_mid - 2 * bb_std

Portfolio Risk Mathematics

# Sharpe Ratio
excess_returns = portfolio_returns - risk_free_rate
sharpe = (excess_returns.mean() * 252) / (excess_returns.std() * np.sqrt(252))

# Maximum Drawdown
cumulative = (1 + portfolio_returns).cumprod()
running_max = cumulative.cummax()
drawdown = (cumulative - running_max) / running_max
max_drawdown = drawdown.min()

# Value at Risk (95%)
var_95 = np.percentile(portfolio_returns, 5)
06

AI & LLM Integration

Agent Design Patterns

Each AI agent follows a consistent pattern:

  1. Context assembly ‚Äî Structured data from MCP Gateway formatted into detailed prompts
  2. Domain-specific system prompt ‚Äî Agents primed with investment domain expertise (Sentiment scores on [‚àí1, +1], Fundamental Agent evaluates like a "quantitative analyst", Competitor Agent compares valuation, growth, and moat)
  3. Structured output ‚Äî LLM responses parsed and routed to frontend components

LLM Selection Rationale

Google Gemini 3 Pro was chosen for its large context window (handles substantial multi-factor prompts), strong quantitative reasoning, competitive pricing, and low latency sufficient for real-time SSE streaming.

07

Design Philosophy

Separation of Data & Intelligence

MCP Gateway handles data fetching and computation. AI agents focus purely on interpretation. Each layer is independently testable and swappable.

Server-side Compute, Client-side Viz

Indicators computed in Python (pandas/NumPy), visualized in browser via Plotly.js. Server sends chart-ready JSON, not raw dataframes.

SSE over WebSockets

Server-Sent Events are sufficient for unidirectional streaming and simpler to implement with FastAPI. Each agent completion emits a progress event.

Human-in-the-Loop

LangGraph interrupt before the Writer agent ensures users review raw findings before final synthesis ‚Äî mirroring institutional research workflows.

Local-First Architecture

All processing and storage happens locally. Only LLM inference calls leave the network, minimizing exposure for sensitive portfolio data.

Robust Data Handling

Custom safe_float/safe_int helpers handle NaN/Inf from financial data, preventing serialization crashes in production.
